The memcmp compares sizeof(entry->userhash_sha256) bytes from both entry->userhash_sha256 and the caller-supplied userhash pointer. While the entry side is safe (the loop bounds ensure entry points inside the user_ids array and the code checks sizeof(...) == userhash_size), there is no check that the userhash pointer actually points to an object at least userhash_size bytes long (or is non-NULL). If the caller passes a pointer to a smaller buffer (or NULL) while reporting userhash_size equal to the hash size, memcmp will read beyond the bounds of the object referenced by userhash and thus violate Rule 21.17.
